\begin_layout Subsection
Outcome Variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:outcome-variables"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure outcomes at three levels of the value chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the MCC level,
 primary outcomes capture the adoption of quality testing infrastructure and the emergence of quality-based pricing.
 Testing outcomes include whether the MCC uses the milk analyzer to test incoming milk deliveries and whether it tests outgoing milk sold to processors.
 Pricing outcomes include the average price paid to farmers for milk,
 the average price received from buyers,
 and whether the MCC gives or receives quality-based bonuses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farmer level,
 primary outcomes capture changes in production practices and market returns.
 These include an index of improved dairy management practices (oversowing,
 legume pastures,
 controlled grazing,
 pasture conservation,
 and supplementary feeding),
 whether the farmer's buyer uses a milk analyzer for quality testing,
 the quantity-weighted average sales price received,
 and whether the farmer receives a quality bonus from any buyer.
 We combine these four outcomes into an Anderson index as a summary measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 to obtain objective measures of milk quality independent of self-reported survey data,
 we collect supervised milk samples at endline.
 Enumerators equipped with project Lactoscans visited each MCC and tested all incoming deliveries over one full day,
 yielding measurements of butterfat,
 solids-not-fat,
 protein,
 added water,
 and corrected lactometer reading for each delivery.
 These sample-level outcomes are analyzed using quantity-weighted least squares,
 with treatment effects identified from the MCC-level randomization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondary outcome families,
 reported in the appendix,
 include sales quantities,
 treatment uptake indicators,
 sales channel choices,
 and MCC-level farmer counts and volumes.
\end_layout

