\begin_layout Standard
While our power calculations relied on models that include the full set of interactions,
 an important feature of split-plot (factorial) designs is that statistical power to estimate the effect of one treatment can be increased by pooling observations across the orthogonal treatment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "list2011so"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In our case,
 this means that the effect of the farmer-level intervention can be estimated by pooling across MCC-level treatment arms,
 and conversely the effect of the MCC-level intervention can be estimated by pooling across farmer-level treatment arms.
 At the same time,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "muralidharan2019factorial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 cautions against indiscriminate pooling of treatment cells when the underlying interventions may exhibit interaction effects.
 The authors note that,
 in the presence of even modest complementarities or antagonisms between treatment components,
 pooling can lead to biased or misleading estimates of marginal treatment effects.
 Consequently,
 they argue that a more rigorous and defensible approach is to estimate fully interacted specifications,
 which allow each treatment combination to have its own effect and thereby avoid imposing potentially unwarranted additivity assumptions.
 One way to recover an unbiased estimate of the pooled main treatment effect is to consider the orthogonal treatment as a co-variate and adjust for it,
 entering it in the regression demeaned and fully interacted as in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pooled-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pooled-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is important to note that the estimand of the respective treatments in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pooled-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pooled-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 changes.
 For instance,
 while the estimand for the MCC-level treatment (T1) in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:one-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is the effect of the treatment in and of itself,
 the estimand in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pooled-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is a weighted average of the pure effect of the MCC-level treatment (T1) and the effect of the T1 in the presence of T2.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i,m}=\alpha+\beta_{H2}T1_{i,m}+\beta^{T1}_{H3}\left(T2_{i,m}-\bar{T2}\right)+\beta^{T1}_{H4}T1_{i,m}\left(T2_{i,m}-\bar{T2}\right)+\beta_{b}.y^{b}_{i,m}+\varepsilon_{i,m}\label{eq:pooled-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i,m}=\alpha+\beta_{H3}T2_{i,m}+\beta^{T2}_{H2}\left(T1_{i,m}-\bar{T1}\right)+\beta^{T2}_{H4}T2_{i,m}\left(T1_{i,m}-\bar{T1}\right)+\beta_{b}.y^{b}_{i,m}+\varepsilon_{i,m}\label{eq:pooled-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all farmer level regressions,
 we apply a cluster-robust variance estimator with the bias-reduced linearization (CR2) small-sample correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/REST_a_00552"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 with standard errors clustered at the level of randomization (MCC catchment area level).
 To account for multiple comparisons,
 we will combine primary outcomes into an index following
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1198/016214508000000841"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the CR2-based inference described above,
 we also report Fisher randomization inference (RI) p-values as our primary inferential framework,
 computed from 5,000 permutations that respect the experimental design:
 the measurement and monitoring system treatment is permuted at the MCC level (maintaining the number of treated MCCs),
 and the video treatment is permuted within each MCC (maintaining counts).
 For multiple testing,
 we report an omnibus count test following the EGAP approach:
 under the sharp null of no treatment effect,
 we compute the probability of observing as many individually significant outcomes as in the actual data.
 CR2 cluster-robust p-values,
 Anderson-Sharp q-values,
 and further robustness checks are reported in the appendix.
\end_layout

