\begin_layout Section
A Model of Quality Infrastructure and Quality Incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:model"

\end_inset

This section presents a simple analytical framework to interpret the findings from both experiments.
 The model formalizes two channels through which quality infrastructure can affect outcomes: an enforcement channel, in which improved measurement precision makes rejection thresholds credibly binding, and a price channel, in which quality measurement enables quality-differentiated pricing.
 The Experiment 1 results are consistent with the enforcement channel operating in isolation: quality improves but prices do not differentiate.
 Experiment 2 then tests the price channel directly by exogenously activating quality-based premiums.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment and Timing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is one processor,
 multiple MCCs indexed by 
\emph on
m
\emph default
,
 and,
 within each MCC catchment,
 multiple farmers indexed by 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 that deliver milk to the MCC.
 The quantity of milk supplied by farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 is assumed to be fixed in the short run,
 as it primarily depends on the farmer’s herd size,
 which does not adjust quickly.
 Milk quality is expressed on a continuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{i}\in\left[0,1\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 and reflects compositional attributes such as butterfat and SNF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After observing delivered quantities and a (possibly noisy) signal of quality for each farmer,
 the MCC decides whether to accept or reject each delivery.
 Accepted milk is aggregated and sold to the processor,
 who pays a premium for verifiable compositional quality.
 The downstream price received by the MCC therefore depends on average quality of accepted milk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A critical feature of the model is how the MCC observes quality.
 Without measurement technology, the MCC observes a noisy signal of farmer
\emph on
i
\emph default
's quality:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
s_{i}=q_{i}+\eta_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}\sim N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 is measurement noise independent of the quality shock
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 With only basic tools (lactometer, alcohol test),
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is large: the MCC can detect gross adulteration but cannot precisely assess compositional quality.
 The introduction of a milk analyzer reduces
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 toward zero, enabling precise measurement of butterfat, SNF, protein, and added water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceptance decision is based on the observed signal:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
a_{i}=\mathbf{1}\left\{ s_{i}\geq q_{min}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

rather than true quality
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This distinction is central: when
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is high, the acceptance threshold is only weakly enforced because the MCC cannot reliably distinguish high-quality from low-quality milk.
 Reducing
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 makes the threshold credibly binding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers differ in how they are connected to the MCC:
 some deliver directly;
 others deliver through intermediaries.
