\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of Improved Measurement Precision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central comparative static for Experiment 1 concerns the effect of reducing measurement noise
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the acceptance probability:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\pi_{i}\left(e_{i};q_{min},\sigma^{2}\right)=1-\Phi\left(\frac{q_{min}-\theta_{i}e_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2}+\sigma^{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Reducing
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (improving measurement precision) has two effects.
 First, for farmers whose expected quality
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is close to but above the threshold
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

, acceptance becomes more certain, reducing the risk of false rejection.
 Second, and more importantly, for farmers whose expected quality is near or below the threshold, the probability of rejection increases sharply.
 The threat of rejection, previously weakened by the noise in the MCC's observation, becomes credible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This tightening of the acceptance probability distribution around the threshold generates an incentive for farmers near the margin to increase effort:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial e_{i}^{*}}{\partial\sigma^{2}}<0\quad\text{when }\theta_{i}e_{i}\text{ is near }q_{min}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, better measurement (lower
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

) induces higher effort from farmers who are close to the acceptance threshold.
 Crucially, this mechanism operates entirely through the extensive margin (acceptance probability) and does not require any price differentiation (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can be zero).
 The model therefore predicts that measurement technology can improve quality purely through more credible enforcement, without any change in the price schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the enforcement channel.
 Its key empirical signatures are: (i) quality improves, particularly through reduced adulteration (the quality dimension most directly affected by effort near the threshold); (ii) prices do not change (because
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

); (iii) the quality improvement is concentrated at the lower tail of the distribution (farmers near
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 adjust, while those already well above the threshold do not).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enforcement channel explains the Experiment 1 results: quality improves through more credible rejection threats, but prices do not differentiate.
 The model, however, also generates predictions about what would happen if quality-based pricing were activated, i.e., if
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 were exogenously increased from zero.
 This motivates Experiment 2, which directly tests these predictions by providing quality premiums to traders.
\end_layout

